The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Saturday, June 12, 2004 				 Bidders pay big for little bit of Hepburn
New York, June 11 (Reuters): Bidding was brisk for items auctioned from the estate of actress Katharine Hepburn today with a brooch given to her by then-boyfriend Howard Hughes fetching $120,000, six times its estimated price.																								The platinum, diamond and sapphire brooch had been estimated to fetch just $20,000 by Sothebys, which said 222 lots sold in the first of three sessions brought just under $1.8 million. Some 400 collectors and fans crowded into Sothebys for the sale of property belonging to Hepburn, a four-time Academy Award winner, who died last June at age 96.																								Hundreds of items, including Hepburns wedding dress, photos, letters, art work and furniture from her homes in Connecticut, New York and Los Angeles and drawings and paintings done by the actress herself were on offer.																								The second highest price paid at the first session was $102,000 for a seascape oil painting Mending the Nets, by William Nicholson.																								A silver cigarette box engraved with the signatures of her fellow cast members of the 1941 stage production of The Philadelphia Story, sold for $57,000. A self-portrait entitled Breakfast in Bed, A Self-Portrait in Brisbane, Australia, 1955 fetched $33,000, some 40 times the estimated price.																								Hepburns unusual wedding dress, made of crushed white velvet with antiqued gold embroidery. sold for $27,000. Her 1928 marriage to Ludlow Ogden Smith lasted six years and Hepburn never remarried.																								The daughter of a Connecticut doctor and a mother who fought for womens rights, Hepburns acting career spanned seven decades, from 1932 to 1994.
